post_text:
Ethan Grefsrud Volleyball Camp.
Elementary Fieldhouse

August 3-5: Grades 6-8: 9-11am. Grades 9-12: 11am-2pm.

Limit of 22 participants

Home grown to Hawley, Ethan Grefsrud, currently Head Coach for Red River Infinity Volleyball Club in Fargo, ND and 16's National Head Coach. Grefsrud is responsible for all technical skills training, game strategy and mentoring coaches.

Grefsrud spent the 2017 volleyball season as the Volunteer Assistant Coach at the University of Wisconsin as a Badger.

$75 for grades 6-8, includes t shirt

$115 for grades 9-12, includes t shirt

Participants are required to read and sign COVID-19 waiver for camps found on Community Ed tab of Hawley Public School Website - disregard the baseball statement at the end of the waiver and write in volleyball.

Hawley Baseball
June 22 at 12:17 PM ·

SUMMER BASEBALL UPDATE

It's still not too late to sign up for summer baseball opportunities in Hawley sponsored by Hawley Community Education! Click on the link below - then click on the 2020 SUMMER REC REGISTRATION link to register your child.

https://www.hawley.k12.mn.us/page/2892

Programs will begin on July 6th. Practices dates and specific times for Babe Ruth players will be based on the number of participants. Practices will likely be in the afternoon Monday thru Thursday three to four days a week thru July 30th.

For elementary-aged campers, all boys will receive a free T-shirt as part of their registration for the camps. Social Distancing measures will be posted soon as we await what the final numbers will be for each camp.

Batting Cages and Fields out at the Rodeo Grounds continue to be open for use. Please practice proper social distancing and sanitizing.

Look for a Senior Babe Ruth Baseball update soon including information about the game schedule.

post_text:
May 14, 2020

Parents/Guardians/Students,

Hawley Community Education would like to share a few updates with you related to summer recreation activities.

It is with much consideration for the regard to safety that Summer Recreation classes and activities have been cancelled except for a few virtual activities for June. You will be able to register for these virtual classes next week on-line on the Hawley School Website under the Community Education Tab. We are not making any decisions for July classes at this time. It is possible that some activities that were planned for June could be rescheduled for July. We are committed to doing everything that we can to offer students opportunities to be active and participate this summer all while following guidance from the Governor, MN Department of Health and the MN Department of Education.

If you have any questions or ideas for virtual classes, feel free to contact Community Education at 218-483-3555 X1012 or bgottenborg@hawley.k12.mn.us.

Thank you very much for your patience during this time.

post_text:
These next few days are dedicated to the class of 2020. Each day a group (alphabetical order) of seniors will be honored. Thank you Mrs. Siegel for the slide show.

To the class of 2020:

This is not how you or the staff at Hawley High School wanted to see your grade school career end. You have worked long and hard to reach this milestone. Friendships and many memories have been made these past 13 years. Be proud of what you have accomplished. You have become a class who thrived during a time when ‘normal’ changed. Only the class of 2020 will have these stories to tell. You will always be remembered, not as the class who did not have a ‘normal’ graduation, but as a class of strength. You are the Hawley High School Class of 2020 and your parents, the staff, and the community of Hawley could not be more proud of you.

post_text:
Minnesota schools are joining in to turn on stadium lights during select evening hours as a way to honor their students, staff and community members in this time of distance learning while school buildings are closed due to Covid-19 concerns. #BeTheLightMN

Hawley Public Schools will join schools around Minnesota to #BeTheLightMN. The Dale Skallerud Athletic Complex on the campus of Hawley Public Schools will turn on the stadium lights starting at 8:20 pm on Monday April 6 for 20 minutes. This will be done each Monday for the remainder of the school year to honor the 8 remaining weeks of school for all students & the class of 2020 in particular.

An important reminder: Please do not gather near or under the lights. Enjoy from afar, maintain proper social distancing and please stay safe and keep others safe.
text:
Minnesota schools are joining in to turn on stadium lights during select evening hours as a way to honor their students, staff and community members in this time of distance learning while school buildings are closed due to Covid-19 concerns. #BeTheLightMN

Hawley Public Schools will join schools around Minnesota to #BeTheLightMN. The Dale Skallerud Athletic Complex on the campus of Hawley Public Schools will turn on the stadium lights starting at 8:20 pm on Monday April 6 for 20 minutes. This will be done each Monday for the remainder of the school year to honor the 8 remaining weeks of school for all students & the class of 2020 in particular.

An important reminder: Please do not gather near or under the lights. Enjoy from afar, maintain proper social distancing and please stay safe and keep others safe.

Also, for the scheduled pick up of materials for elementary students whose teacher has indicated they have materials to pick up (and library books), they can come to the elementary school Monday, April 6 from 6:00am to 6:00pm. Sorry for the inconvenience.

Stay safe everyone!

Chris Ellingson
Elementary Principal

post_text:
Hawley Public School will be closed Wednesday, March 18 - Friday, March 27, 2020 per the directive of the state.

Base will be available for students whose parents/guardians work in the healthcare field, including first responders. We are also working on a meal plan for students.

Our staff will be preparing for e-learning. More information will be provided throughout the week as we get clarification on specifics and work out the details.

Thank you for your patience as this is uncharted territory for us and we want to ensure that we are doing all we can to both keep our students and staff safe while providing quality education

In light of everything that is going on, we will postponing the Elementary Public Performance of the Musical Frozen.

It is our hope that in the near future we will be able to have a public show as the cast, crew, and advisors put in a lot of hard work and we want to share that with all of you. I apologize for the short notice, but at this point it is best to error on the side of caution and postpone the performance for the time being.

Thank you all for your understanding and hopefully soon we will be able to have the students share their talents with all of you!

Chris Ellingson

Congratulations to the following FFA teams who did well at regional competition yesterday:

Ag Mechanics - 1st,
Crops – 1st,
Floriculture – 2nd
Horse – 6th.
Ag Mechanics, Crops and Floriculture will advance to state in April.

Individually Hawley did very well also.

In Ag Mechanics Isaiah Specht finished 1st, Sam Helgeson – 3rd , Wyatt Dunham – 6th and Shea Hocket was also on the winning team.

In Crops Owen Aakre was 1st, Ethen Vind was 4th and Chase Hovelson was 7th.

Floriculture Beth Goodhart finished 2nd, Jeremy Fenske was 5th, Kaitlyn Rux finished 8th and Levi Mickelson was 9th.

The Horse team was made up of the following 7th and 8th graders: Briley Heng, Tyler Demmer, Hattie Jackson, Amelia Joy and Abby Anderson.

Great job everyone!

post_text:
Attention 2020 Prom Attendees!!

Prom Ticket sales will begin March 2nd and continue through March 13th. For those of you who did not sell $60 worth of beef raffle tickets, you will need to purchase a ticket from Mrs. Specht. If you are taking someone from the sophomore class or someone from out of town, you must buy a ticket for them during the 2 week Prom Ticket sales window. Prom tickets are $60 each. If you sold $60 worth of beef raffle tickets to cover your ticket cost and have turned in the money and beef raffle tickets to Mrs. Specht, you do not need buy a Prom ticket, you are covered by your beef raffle ticket sales. Again, if you are a senior who went to prom last year or paid your class dues in full last year, you do not have to buy a Prom ticket for yourself. Please make sure you have a prom ticket purchased by March 13th as the ticket price will increase to $65 after that date. Sign up for banquet tables will occur in April.

Stephanie Specht
Prom Adviser

post_text:
Congratulations to Hayden Hogenson for earning a Scholastic Gold Key Award in Poetry!

There are 2 divisions of the Scholastic Awards: Art and Writing. Within the divisions there are different categories for submission. At the state level Hayden participated in the writing division and submitted 5 poems that were intertwined titled, "Mine to Keep". Art teacher, Tara Hager, had to approve of the work locally before submitting for competition.

At the state level 47 pieces received awards (honorable mention, silver and gold keys). 11 of the 47 pieces earned gold key honors. From here Hayden's poems will compete at the national level against work from all over the country. Hayden will be recognized in February in Minneapolis.

Way to go Hayden!

post_text:
Congratulations Emily Tjaden!
Emily Tjaden has been recognized by the Scholastic Art Awards…

Emily received four awards!!

Honorable mention – Painting
Silver Key – Printmaking
Gold Key
Gold Key – Drawing
Gold Key – Portfolio (This is honestly a massive amount of work) – so proud of Emily

• FYI - Gold Key The very best works submitted to local programs. Gold Key works are automatically considered for national recognition. Artwork receiving a Gold Key Award is included in the Gold Key Exhibition at Regis West Gallery.

The Scholastic Art Awards are open to all art students age 13 or older in grades 7 - 12 from public, private and home schools and community programs serving eligible student populations. Students receive opportunities for recognition, exhibition, and scholarships. The Scholastic Art Awards have been around since 1923! This art competition receives thousands of art submissions…soooooo, this is a REALLY big deal and VERY competitive.

Congrats Emily!
